// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  PMP EXAM MASTERY — MOCK TEST 5 (180 Questions)
//  Distribution: People ~42% (76q) | Process ~50% (90q) | Business ~8% (14q)
//  Exposed as window.PMP_MOCK_TEST_5
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
window.PMP_MOCK_TEST_5 = [

// ─────────────────────────── PEOPLE DOMAIN (~76 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager joins an agile team mid-project. During the first retrospective they attend, team members give only surface-level answers and avoid discussing real issues.', question:'What does this indicate and what should the PM do?', options:['The team has no real issues — surface feedback means everything is fine','This indicates low psychological safety — team members don\'t feel safe discussing real problems with a new authority figure present. The PM should: consider initially observing retros without participating, explicitly invite candor, share their own vulnerabilities first, establish retro ground rules, and build trust through consistent confidential follow-through before expecting deep candor.','The team is performing at a high level and doesn\'t need retrospectives','Mandate that all team members share at least 3 improvement areas each'], correct:1, explanation:'Psychological safety (Amy Edmondson\'s research) is the prerequisite for honest retrospectives. A new PM\'s presence can undermine it — even with good intentions. Signals of low safety: vague, positive-only feedback; no one raises real pain points; everyone defers to what others say. Building safety requires: modeling vulnerability (sharing your own mistakes and uncertainties), consistent non-punitive response to concerns raised, protecting what\'s shared in retros from performance management consequences, and proving through actions that candor is rewarded, not punished. Trust must be earned before deep honesty can be expected.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is managing a team of subject matter experts who all have more domain knowledge than the PM. Team members frequently challenge the PM\'s technical recommendations.', question:'What is the MOST effective leadership approach?', options:['Assert authority to maintain credibility and control','Embrace a facilitative, expertise-leveraging leadership model: acknowledge openly that team members have deeper domain expertise, position your value as integration, facilitation, and governance — not technical direction. Channel the team\'s expertise through structured decision processes while maintaining accountability for project outcomes.','Develop technical expertise in all domains to establish credibility','Delegate all technical decisions to the most senior SME'], correct:1, explanation:'Leading SMEs requires a different authority model than traditional PM. Positional authority ("I\'m the PM") is insufficient when team members know more about the work than you do. Your value proposition: integration (connecting expertise across domains), facilitation (enabling effective decisions across competing expert opinions), governance (ensuring decisions are documented and governed properly), and stakeholder management (translating technical work into business language). Openly acknowledging expertise asymmetry builds credibility — trying to fake domain expertise destroys it. This is adaptive leadership (PMBOK 7 Principle #6) — your style fits the team\'s needs.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An agile team member completes all their assigned work by Wednesday of every sprint but refuses to pull new work from the backlog, saying "I\'ve done my part — the sprint goal is the team\'s collective problem."', question:'What should the Scrum Master/PM do?', options:['Reassign remaining work to this team member since they finished early','Facilitate a team discussion on collective ownership and swarming: in agile, the sprint goal belongs to the TEAM, not to individuals. Individual completion while the team misses the sprint goal is failure. Coaching: when your tasks are done and the team has unfinished stories, the highest-value activity is helping teammates complete the sprint goal.','Accept the individual\'s work style since they met their personal commitments','Increase the individual\'s personal workload so they are occupied until sprint end'], correct:1, explanation:'Individual-over-team orientation is an agile anti-pattern. The sprint is a team event with a shared goal — not a set of individual micro-deliverables. When one person finishes while others struggle, the highest-value action is swarming: help the struggling team members complete their stories, do test support, documentation, or exploratory testing. This is the agile principle of collective code ownership extended to collective sprint ownership. The coaching conversation: "our goal this sprint was X, not just our individual stories. What can you do to help us hit the goal?" This shifts identity from individual contributor to team player.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager\'s performance review includes a 360-degree feedback component. Several team members independently rate the PM low on "creates clarity of direction" and "provides timely decisions."', question:'What should the project manager do with this feedback?', options:['Dismiss the feedback since project decisions involve uncertainty that teams don\'t understand','Take the feedback seriously as a signal of leadership impact. Investigate specific instances where direction was unclear or decisions were delayed, identify root causes (fear of wrong decisions? insufficient information? unclear decision authority?), and create specific behavioral changes: decision timeboxes, clearer communication of rationale, and explicit escalation protocols for decisions beyond PM authority.','Conduct individual meetings to find out who gave the low ratings','Defend the current approach in the 360-degree feedback response as contextually appropriate'], correct:1, explanation:'360-degree feedback from multiple independent sources is credible signal, not noise to dismiss. "Creates clarity" and "timely decisions" are leadership behaviors with direct impact on team effectiveness — teams that lack direction slow down, make assumptions, and produce rework. The PM should investigate: specific instances, root causes (information gaps? risk aversion? authority ambiguity?), and make behavioral changes. Decision timeboxes ("I will decide X by end of day Friday regardless of perfect information") address delay. Written decision rationale addresses clarity. This is leader self-development — a professional maturity that distinguishes great PMs.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team is developing a product for users who speak Swahili as their primary language. The team has no native Swahili speakers. Quality acceptance testing shows high user error rates with the current UI.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Accept the error rates since non-native language usage inevitably creates friction','Engage native Swahili-speaking user representatives for usability testing, include localization and UX translation review as project deliverables, and consider adding a Swahili-speaking UX consultant to the team. The user error rates signal that translation/localization is a quality failure that must be addressed before delivery.','Provide more training materials to help users adapt to the existing interface','Release the current version and plan a localization improvement in the next version'], correct:1, explanation:'High user error rates from language/localization mismatch are a quality failure, not a user problem. The solution requires: native language usability testing (users testing with native fluency), professional UX-aware translation (not just word-for-word), and cultural UX adaptation (iconography, interaction patterns, reading direction may differ). This is quality management applied to localization — treating user error rates as defect indicators that must be resolved before acceptance. "Fix it in the next version" after release to 50,000 users creates real harm (errors in critical tasks) and brand damage. This is product quality stewardship.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'During a planning session, a project team member proposes a solution that the PM knows is technically incorrect based on the PM\'s own domain experience. However, the team member is junior and presenting confidently.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Allow the junior team member\'s proposal to proceed to avoid undermining their confidence','Raise the technical concern directly but respectfully: ask clarifying questions that lead the team member to discover the flaw themselves, or explicitly but non-confrontationally identify the technical issue ("I want to make sure we consider X — can you walk us through how this solution handles that case?"). The team member\'s confidence grows through learning, not through uncorrected mistakes.','Implement the solution and let the consequences demonstrate the error','Tell the team member privately after the meeting that their proposal was incorrect'], correct:1, explanation:'A PM with domain expertise has a responsibility to prevent known technical errors from becoming project failures — silence is not mentorship. The approach matters: Socratic questioning ("how does this handle edge case X?") is preferable to direct correction because it engages the team member\'s thinking and creates more durable learning than being told. Public humiliation damages psychological safety; Socratic challenge done with genuine curiosity does not. If Socratic questioning doesn\'t surface the issue, the PM must be clear ("I\'m concerned about X because Y — can we explore this further?"). This is coaching with technical accountability.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is leading a team that has developed a strong bond and high performance over 18 months. The project is ending, and team members will be reassigned to different projects and departments.', question:'What should the PM do during project closure to manage the team\'s transition?', options:['Focus only on technical project closure activities since reassignment is an HR matter','Acknowledge the team\'s journey and achievement (the Adjourning stage of Tuckman\'s model is real and emotionally significant), create meaningful closure experiences (final retrospective, team celebration, individualized recognition), provide strong reference letters, and connect team members with their new PM/manager in a warm handover that sets them up for success.','Avoid acknowledging the end to maintain team focus on remaining tasks','Assign team members to new projects immediately to minimize transition downtime'], correct:1, explanation:'Tuckman\'s Adjourning stage is often undermanaged. High-performing teams develop genuine bonds that deserve acknowledgment when they dissolve. Meaningful closure: final retrospective (what did we accomplish together? what did we learn?), celebration of collective achievement, individualized recognition of each person\'s specific contribution, and strong career support (reference letters, network introductions). This is stewardship for people beyond the project boundary. Teams that experience positive closure carry those norms, relationships, and capabilities into their next projects — creating organizational culture that benefits future work. This is leadership at its most human.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An agile team\'s velocity has increased by 50% over the last 4 sprints. The Product Owner is excited and immediately increases the sprint commitment by 50% for the next sprint.', question:'What concern should the Scrum Master/PM raise?', options:['No concern — velocity increase is always positive and should be rewarded with higher commitments','Investigate the velocity increase before assuming it reflects real improvement: is it from genuine productivity improvement (team got better) or from gaming (reducing story point size, accepting incomplete work as done, reducing quality checks)? If genuine, moderate increase in commitment with team agreement. If gaming, address immediately.','Double the commitment since velocity could still increase further','Ask the PO to reduce the commitment since velocity increases are always temporary'], correct:1, explanation:'Velocity spikes require investigation before being celebrated or extrapolated. Legitimate velocity increases: team mastered the technology stack, cross-training improved collaboration, impediments were removed. Gaming red flags: story point deflation (same stories now estimated smaller), DoD shortcuts (accepting stories without full quality checks), or increased technical debt accumulation. If velocity is genuine, a moderate commitment increase with team agreement is appropriate — not an immediate 50% jump which risks a confidence-destroying sprint collapse. The Scrum Master\'s role is empirical verification, not cheerleading. This protects the team from unrealistic commitments based on potentially artifactual data.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is introducing a new automated testing framework to the team. Two senior developers resist, saying the new framework will slow them down and their manual testing is sufficient.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Override their resistance and mandate the framework since it is a project decision','Engage the senior developers as co-designers of the framework implementation: understand their specific objections (workflow disruption? learning curve? distrust of automation quality?), involve them in selecting configuration and coverage, create a pilot period with defined success metrics, and use their expertise to make the implementation better — converting resistant experts into implementation champions.','Implement the framework for junior developers only and allow seniors to continue manually','Accept the seniors\' position since they have the most testing experience'], correct:1, explanation:'Expert resistance to new tools is often expertise-based (they\'ve seen poor tool implementations), not change aversion. The PM should leverage this: ask specifically what would need to be true for them to support the framework. Often: control over configuration, proven coverage metrics, and a fair pilot period. Involving resistant experts as co-designers (not just informed recipients) converts their expertise from a blocking force to an enabling one. Their concerns often improve the implementation — they\'ve thought about the edge cases. This is change management at the individual level — the most effective approach for resistant subject matter experts.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager has a team member who constantly interrupts during brainstorming sessions with "we tried that before and it didn\'t work" without providing context on what failed or why.', question:'How should the PM handle this in brainstorming facilitation?', options:['Accept the historical knowledge as valuable and avoid pursuing the ideas they dismiss','Establish a "suspend judgment" ground rule for brainstorming (diverge before converging), use a "parking lot" for concerns (captured but not evaluated yet), and invite historical context in the convergence phase: "In the evaluation phase, please share what specifically failed and why — that\'s critical information for our decision." This preserves creative space while valuing institutional memory.','Exclude the negative team member from future brainstorming sessions','Challenge the team member publicly to provide evidence for their claim'], correct:1, explanation:'Historical knowledge is valuable — but premature criticism during brainstorming kills creative flow. Brainstorming requires a divergent phase (generate ideas without judgment) before a convergent phase (evaluate and decide). The "suspend judgment" rule enables divergence. The parking lot captures concerns without letting them dominate. During convergence, the team member\'s institutional knowledge is invited explicitly and in context — "what failed? what specifically? what conditions might be different now?" This transforms a meeting disruptor into a valuable risk informant at the right time. Facilitation design is a PM competency that creates meeting environments where diverse contributions are extractable.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team has been asked to deliver under an aggressive timeline. The PM knows the timeline is technically infeasible without sacrificing quality. The project sponsor is insisting.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Commit to the timeline and plan to address quality issues after delivery','Present the sponsor with a quantified trade-off analysis: what specific quality elements would be sacrificed to meet the timeline, what is the probability and cost of quality failures post-deployment, and propose alternative options (partial delivery of highest-value scope, phased timeline, additional resources). Do not commit to an infeasible timeline.','Commit to the timeline and secretly plan to miss it','Ask team members to work overtime to make the infeasible timeline feasible'], correct:1, explanation:'PMI\'s ethics code requires honest communication about feasibility — committing to what you know is infeasible is deceptive. The PM\'s professional obligation: present honest trade-off analysis. The sponsor may not understand what "quality sacrifice" means concretely — make it specific: "Meeting this timeline means skipping integration testing, which our historical data shows results in 3× post-deployment defect rates." With concrete consequences, sponsors often make different choices. If the sponsor still insists despite honest disclosure, the PM documents the decision and its rationale, implements with best efforts, and monitors closely. The PM\'s accountability is for honest analysis and execution, not for sponsor decisions.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'An agile team\'s retrospective consistently identifies the same issue — "unclear requirements" — sprint after sprint without improvement.', question:'What should the project manager/Scrum Master do?', options:['Accept that unclear requirements are inherent in agile development','This is a systemic failure requiring root cause analysis at the retrospective-to-action level: why aren\'t retrospective action items producing improvement? Options: PO availability for clarification is structurally inadequate; acceptance criteria standards are not enforced in DoR; the team is pulling too-complex stories without adequate refinement. Identify the specific systemic root cause and design a structural solution, not another retrospective action item.','Blame the Product Owner for failing to write clear requirements','Hold longer refinement sessions until requirements are perfect before sprint planning'], correct:1, explanation:'Recurring retrospective themes that don\'t improve signal one of two problems: (1) the action items defined are not addressing the root cause, or (2) action items are being defined but not followed through. A meta-retrospective ("why do we keep identifying the same issue?") is needed. Common systemic causes for "unclear requirements": PO is not available for real-time clarification during sprints (structural availability problem); no DoR enforcement (stories enter sprints before they\'re ready); team pulls stories that are too large/complex without decomposition. Each cause has a different solution. Longer refinement sessions (option D) addresses symptom, not root cause.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager wants to assess team performance over the past quarter. They are deciding between reviewing delivery metrics (velocity, defect rates) vs. conducting a structured team health assessment (collaboration, communication, morale).', question:'What is the MOST complete approach?', options:['Delivery metrics are sufficient — they objectively measure what matters','Use both: delivery metrics provide quantitative evidence of team output and quality trends; team health assessments provide leading indicators of future performance — teams with declining collaboration and morale predict future velocity drops and quality issues. Health assessments prevent waiting for performance problems to appear in lagging metrics.','Team health assessments are more important since they explain the why behind metrics','Ask individual team members to self-rate their performance'], correct:1, explanation:'Delivery metrics are lagging indicators — they measure what HAS happened. Team health indicators (psychological safety, communication quality, trust, engagement) are leading indicators — they predict what WILL happen. A team with declining morale will show declining velocity in 1-2 sprints. Identifying health problems early enables intervention before they become performance problems. A complete performance picture uses both: "we delivered X story points at Y quality level (delivery), and our collaboration and communication scores are at Z% (health — this is a leading indicator of next quarter\'s delivery)." This is predictive performance management.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is working on a construction project in a country where "facilitating payments" to local officials are considered normal business practice. A team member suggests making such a payment to accelerate permit approval.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Allow it if the amount is small and the permit is critical','Refuse. Facilitate payments violate international anti-bribery laws (US FCPA, UK Bribery Act), PMI Code of Ethics, and most organizations\' compliance policies — regardless of local cultural norms or business practice. Document the team member\'s suggestion and the PM\'s response. Escalate to organizational compliance/legal team for guidance on legal permit acceleration alternatives.','Allow it if the team member manages the payment without the PM\'s knowledge','Let local partners handle it as a "local business expense"'], correct:1, explanation:'Anti-bribery law is extraterritorial — US and UK anti-bribery laws apply to their citizens and companies regardless of where the payment occurs. "Local custom" is not a legal defense. The PM\'s response must be immediate and clear: no payment, document the suggestion (protective documentation), escalate to compliance. Legal alternatives for permit acceleration exist: legitimate local legal counsel, industry association relationships, formal expedited permit applications. Arranging payments "without PM knowledge" (option C) is willful blindness — legally as bad as direct knowledge. This is professional integrity under cultural pressure — a recurring PMP exam ethics scenario.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is analyzing the results of a team satisfaction survey administered at the midpoint of an 18-month project. The survey shows high task satisfaction but low relationship satisfaction among team members.', question:'What does this indicate and what intervention is appropriate?', options:['Relationship satisfaction is not a project management concern — focus on task performance','This pattern (high task/low relationship) indicates silos: team members are technically effective individually but not functioning as a collaborative unit. Intervention: structured cross-team interaction activities, joint problem-solving sessions, explicit team norms around interpersonal communication, and addressing any specific relationship tensions identified in the survey through private facilitation.','This is a normal pattern for mid-project periods — no intervention needed','Reduce project complexity to create more relationship-building opportunities'], correct:1, explanation:'High task/low relationship satisfaction is a warning pattern: teams can temporarily perform well as parallel individual contributors, but sustained high performance requires collaborative relationships. Mid-project is an ideal intervention point — 9 months remain to build the collaborative foundation that will sustain performance through the project\'s most challenging final phases. Silos in mid-project create communication failures in the complex final integration and testing phases. Interventions: team norm workshops (how do we want to work together?), cross-team pair work (force collaborative interaction), conflict resolution for any identified tensions. Acting now is preventive; acting at project end is too late.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager notices that during team meetings, the same three team members speak 90% of the time, while five other team members rarely contribute.', question:'What facilitation technique addresses this specifically?', options:['Let the dynamic continue since the three vocal members have the most valuable ideas','Use structured facilitation: equal speaking time allocation (round-robin), silent brainstorming before discussion (each person writes ideas before speaking), "nominal group technique" (everyone writes independently, ideas are aggregated anonymously, then discussed), and direct solicitation of quiet members\' views by the facilitator. Meeting design that creates contribution structure is more effective than hoping quiet members will self-advocate.','Limit vocal members to two contributions per meeting','Schedule separate meetings with quiet members to gather their input'], correct:1, explanation:'Participation inequality in meetings has structural causes: dominant personalities, hierarchical dynamics, social anxiety, cultural deference, or disengagement. Facilitation techniques that work structurally: silent brainstorming prevents vocal dominance (ideas are generated simultaneously, not sequentially). Nominal group technique makes all ideas visible before discussion begins. Round-robin creates equal speaking turns. Direct solicitation ("Maria, what\'s your take on this?") signals that quiet voices are valued. Limiting vocal members is adversarial and creates resentment. Separate meetings for quiet members are informative but don\'t build the group\'s collaborative capacity. The goal is equitable participation design.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project is transitioning from a highly predictive approach to an agile approach due to changing organizational strategy. Several experienced project managers on the team are resistant.', question:'What approach is MOST effective for managing this change?', options:['Mandate the transition and implement consequences for non-compliance','Acknowledge the legitimate experience and concerns of resistant PMs, involve them in designing the agile implementation (how agile applies to this specific project context), provide hands-on agile training paired with practical application, create peer learning opportunities with agile practitioners, and establish psychological safety for learning through experimentation rather than expecting immediate expertise.','Replace resistant PMs with agile-experienced practitioners','Implement agile for some projects while allowing resistant PMs to use predictive for others'], correct:1, explanation:'Experienced PMs who have mastered one methodology are being asked to become learners again — which can feel threatening to professional identity. The approach that works: acknowledge their expertise ("your planning and risk management skills transfer directly to agile"), involve them in adaptation design ("how should we apply this in our context?"), provide genuine learning support (not just a 2-day workshop), and create safety for imperfect agile practice during the learning curve. Involving them in design creates ownership. Mandating compliance without respect creates resistance underground (they comply in name but undermine in practice). This is the Change Management approach to methodology transition.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project team includes members at very different career stages: two junior members (2 years experience) and two senior members (15+ years experience). The PM wants to structure the team\'s work to develop all members.', question:'What assignment approach serves both performance and development?', options:['Assign seniors to all complex work and juniors to all routine tasks','Create paired assignments: pair junior members with seniors on complex deliverables with clearly defined learning objectives, allow juniors to lead specific deliverables with senior mentoring, and give seniors \'coaching time\' as a recognized project contribution alongside their technical work — making mentoring an explicit project activity, not an informal add-on.','Assign all members equal complexity to create fairness','Separate teams by experience level to optimize individual productivity'], correct:1, explanation:'Paired work is the most effective structure for simultaneous performance and development. Seniors develop leadership and communication skills (teaching requires mastery) while juniors develop technical skills (learning by doing on real work). Junior-led deliverables with senior mentoring give juniors ownership and accountability within a safety net. Making mentoring explicit (in the WBS, in time allocation) signals organizational commitment and prevents mentoring from being sacrificed under delivery pressure. This is PMBOK 6 Develop Team (Section 9.4) applied with intentional design — creating a learning organization within the project team.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is working with a team member who consistently underestimates their tasks, leading to sprint carryover. Despite coaching discussions, the pattern continues for 3 sprints.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Accept the pattern since estimation is inherently imprecise in agile','Move from coaching to structured estimation support: require the team member to decompose all stories into tasks before estimating, pair them with a senior team member for estimation reviews, use historical cycle time data for that team member\'s similar stories, and have explicit checking conversations after 2 days on each story. If the pattern persists with structural support, assess whether there is a capability or personal issue requiring a different intervention.','Assign the team member only tasks that are already estimated by others','Escalate the performance issue to the functional manager after 3 sprints of underperformance'], correct:1, explanation:'Three sprints of coaching without improvement signals that coaching alone is insufficient — structural support is needed. Decomposition before estimation forces explicit task identification (a common source of underestimation). Senior pairing for estimation reviews brings calibration from someone with more experience. Historical cycle time data replaces subjective estimation with empirical evidence. Mid-story check-ins catch scope surprises early when recovery is still possible. If ALL these structural supports don\'t help, then assessment of whether this is a capability issue (needs different work types) or a personal issue (needs EAP support) is appropriate. Escalating to functional manager after 3 sprints without structured support is premature.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project has a designated project management office (PMO) coordinator who handles administrative tasks. The PM notices the coordinator is regularly making decisions that should be within the PM\'s authority without consultation.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Reverse all the coordinator\'s decisions to re-establish authority','Have a private conversation with the coordinator to: understand why decisions were made without consultation (capacity pressure? unclear role boundaries?), review the project RACI clearly with them, establish clear decision escalation protocols, and recognize that the coordinator\'s initiative may be filling a gap the PM should address by being more available for timely decisions.','Document all unauthorized decisions in the coordinator\'s performance file','Escalate to the PMO director about the coordinator\'s behavior'], correct:1, explanation:'PMO coordinators making decisions beyond their authority signals unclear role boundaries or an accessibility gap (PM not available when decisions are needed). Before framing this as misconduct, the PM should investigate: were decisions genuinely within clear PM authority, or was there ambiguity? Was the coordinator filling a vacuum created by PM unavailability? The conversation should: clarify the RACI (what the coordinator can decide vs. must escalate), establish practical escalation paths (when you can\'t reach me, here\'s the protocol), and potentially acknowledge that faster PM responsiveness is needed. Reversing decisions indiscriminately damages the coordinator\'s credibility with stakeholders. This is collaborative role clarification, not punishment.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is facilitating a sprint planning session. The team has difficulty estimating a complex user story because they have never built this type of feature before.', question:'What should happen with this story?', options:['Estimate it high (maximum story points) to be safe','Split the story: create a time-boxed spike (research and exploration task, typically 1-2 days) for the first sprint to investigate the unknowns and produce an updated estimate, then schedule the actual implementation story in the following sprint with a reliable estimate based on spike findings.','Skip the story and move to next sprint\'s planning','Accept any estimate the team provides since all estimates are uncertain anyway'], correct:1, explanation:'A technical spike is the agile mechanism for reducing estimation uncertainty on complex, novel stories. A spike is a fixed-time investigation (timeboxed to 1-2 days) with a specific output: "what do we know after the spike that we didn\'t know before, and what\'s our revised estimate?" Spikes are first-class sprint backlog items. This prevents the team from committing to implementation timelines for work they don\'t yet understand (which produces unreliable sprints), while still making progress in the current sprint (the investigation IS the sprint work). Accepting unreliable estimates perpetuates the sprint carryover problem.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager is preparing for a crucial stakeholder presentation. The most powerful stakeholder group is known to prefer data-driven arguments and resist anecdotal evidence.', question:'What presentation approach is MOST effective?', options:['Use compelling stories and case studies since humans respond better to narratives','Build the presentation around data: quantified project performance metrics, cost-benefit analysis with specific numbers, risk quantification (probability × financial impact), and evidence-based recommendations. Use visuals (charts, not tables) for data comprehension. Lead with the data-supported conclusion, then provide supporting analysis.','Provide both narrative and data in equal measure','Request that stakeholders suspend their data preference for this presentation'], correct:1, explanation:'Stakeholder communication must be tailored to audience preferences and decision-making style. Data-driven stakeholders (often finance, engineering, and analytics leaders) are persuaded by numbers, not stories. Effective data presentation: lead with the conclusion and its data support (don\'t make them wait for the punchline), use visually clear charts (bar, line — not tables of numbers), quantify everything that can be quantified (risk = $X probability × $Y impact = $Z expected value), and prepare for quantitative questions. Narrative storytelling has its place for motivating and connecting, but for decision-makers who trust data, lead with evidence. Knowing your audience is a communication management competency.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'During a team meeting, the project manager proposes a solution and asks for team agreement. All team members nod and say "sounds good." Later, during implementation, it emerges that three team members had significant reservations they didn\'t voice.', question:'What systemic failure occurred and how should the PM prevent it in future?', options:['The team members failed their professional obligation by not speaking up','The meeting design created a conformity pressure that suppressed dissent. Prevention: change the agreement-seeking question ("does everyone agree?") to a specific challenge invitation ("what\'s most likely to go wrong with this approach?"), use anonymous voting tools for sensitive decisions, require explicit challenge from at least one person (devil\'s advocate role), and follow up bilaterally with team members whose body language suggests unvoiced concerns.','This is normal — not everyone has useful input on every decision','Implement the decision and accept that some will agree in public but not in private'], correct:1, explanation:'The failure was in meeting design, not individual team members. "Does everyone agree?" in a group setting creates conformity pressure (social proof, authority deference, meeting fatigue) that suppresses dissent even when people have substantive concerns. Prevention: design meetings that make challenge structurally normal, not optional. Devil\'s advocate role (assigned, not voluntary): one person\'s JOB is to find the flaws. Anonymous voting (poll tools, written votes) removes social pressure. Pre-meeting written input allows asynchronous challenge without public vulnerability. Follow up with those who look skeptical but didn\'t speak. The PM\'s job is to create decision quality, not apparent consensus.' },
  { domain:'People', scenario:'A project manager wants to recognize and reward team performance. The organization\'s HR policy limits formal compensation changes, but the PM wants to provide meaningful recognition.', question:'What non-monetary recognition approaches are MOST effective?', options:['Tell team members their work is appreciated at the next team meeting','Provide specific, timely, individualized recognition: public acknowledgment of specific contributions (named work, specific impact), career development opportunities (leadership of high-visibility deliverables, conference presentations, industry awards nominations), increased autonomy (trust them with greater ownership), and formal feedback for performance records. The specificity and individualization matter more than the form.','Offer team social events as the primary recognition mechanism','Implement a team points system where members earn rewards for completed tasks'], correct:1, explanation:'Recognition research (via Herzberg, Maslow, and Self-Determination Theory) shows that intrinsic recognition is more durable than extrinsic rewards. Effective non-monetary recognition: specific (name the exact contribution, not generic "good job"), timely (close to the event, not months later), public where appropriate (visibility across the organization multiplies the recognition value), and career-enhancing (opportunity to lead a high-visibility workstream, represent the team at a senior meeting, be nominated for an industry award). Generic appreciation at team meetings has minimal motivational value. This is motivation science applied to team management within HR constraints.' },

// ─────────────────────────── PROCESS DOMAIN (~90 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is developing the procurement strategy for a major software development project. The PM must choose between hiring contractors (individual specialists), outsourcing to a systems integrator (single vendor), or building an in-house team.', question:'What factors should drive the procurement strategy decision?', options:['Always choose the lowest-cost option','Evaluate: (1) Make-or-Buy: does this capability need to stay in-house for strategic reasons? (2) Risk: single vendor creates dependency risk; multiple contractors creates coordination complexity. (3) Cost model: contractor flexibility vs. SI efficiency at scale. (4) IP ownership: contractors typically assign IP; check SI contract terms. (5) Timeline: building in-house requires recruiting time. Decision should be based on total cost of ownership, risk profile, and strategic considerations.','Always use a systems integrator to simplify vendor management','Choose based on which approach the team prefers to work with'], correct:1, explanation:'Procurement strategy is a multidimensional decision. Make-or-Buy analysis: is this capability a strategic differentiator that should remain internal? Risk profile: single SI = concentrated vendor dependency risk but simpler coordination; multiple contractors = coordination complexity but no single vendor risk. Cost model: contractors are flexible (can scale up/down) but individually expensive; SI has economies of scale but less flexibility. IP: who owns what is written? Timeline: in-house recruiting takes months. Total Cost of Ownership: include recruiting, management overhead, knowledge transfer, and contract administration. The PM must present a structured analysis of these factors, not default to cost or convenience.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is reviewing a proposed change request that would add AI-powered analytics to an HR platform. The analytics would use employee performance data to predict promotion readiness.', question:'What concerns must be addressed in the change request evaluation?', options:['Only technical feasibility and implementation cost','Technical feasibility AND: (1) Privacy/consent: do employees know their data will be used this way? (2) Bias risk: could the AI model encode historical biases that disadvantage protected groups? (3) Legal compliance: GDPR, CCPA, and employment law implications. (4) Transparency: can employees understand why they were or weren\'t recommended for promotion? (5) Organizational acceptance: how will this affect trust and morale? All must be in the change request.','Only whether the feature is technically possible with available tools','Only whether HR leadership approves the addition'], correct:1, explanation:'AI/ML features involving personal employment data require multi-domain evaluation that goes far beyond technical feasibility. Privacy: was consent obtained for this use? Legal: multiple jurisdictions have AI in employment regulations (EU AI Act classifies this as high-risk). Bias: if historical promotion decisions reflected bias, the AI trained on them will reproduce and automate that bias. Transparency/explainability: affected employees have a right to understand automated decisions that affect their careers. Organizational trust: discovery of hidden algorithmic surveillance of performance data can severely damage employee trust. These are NOT peripheral considerations — they are primary considerations for responsible technology deployment.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A PM is using an agile-waterfall hybrid approach. For the waterfall phases (requirements and architecture), the PM wants to establish clear phase exit criteria. For agile sprints, the PM will use velocity and DoD.', question:'What are appropriate phase exit criteria for the requirements phase?', options:['The requirements phase ends when the schedule says it ends','Phase exit criteria for requirements: (1) All identified stakeholder groups have been consulted and their requirements documented. (2) Requirements have been reviewed and accepted by key stakeholders (formal sign-off). (3) Requirements traceability matrix is complete. (4) Conflicting requirements have been resolved or escalated. (5) Requirements are testable (acceptance criteria defined). (6) Architecture phase start has been confirmed by the team as feasible with these requirements.','Phase exits when the PM decides requirements are good enough','Phase exits when no more new requirements are submitted for 2 weeks'], correct:1, explanation:'Phase exit criteria (also called phase gates or kill/pass criteria) define objective, verifiable conditions that must be met before proceeding to the next phase. For a requirements phase, exit criteria should confirm: completeness (all stakeholders consulted), quality (requirements are testable, unambiguous), coverage (traceability matrix connects all requirements to business objectives), stakeholder acceptance (formal sign-off, not verbal agreement), and feasibility confirmation (architecture team has reviewed and can design to these requirements). "Schedule says so" (option A) is time-based, not quality-based. "No new submissions for 2 weeks" is an arbitrary proxy for completeness. Phase gates are about quality verification, not time passage.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is managing a technically complex data migration project. The team estimates there is a 40% probability that the data cleansing component will require significant rework. The impact of rework is $200,000 and 4 weeks.', question:'What is the Expected Monetary Value of this risk and how should it be used?', options:['EMV = $200,000 (the full impact, since any probability of occurrence warrants full contingency)','EMV = 40% × $200,000 = $80,000. This $80,000 should be part of the contingency reserve calculation for this risk. Additionally, the 4-week schedule risk should be analyzed: 40% × 4 weeks = 1.6 weeks of schedule contingency consideration. EMV does not mean you only prepare $80K of contingency — the full $200K/4-week response plan should be designed and ready.','EMV = $200,000 × 60% = $120,000 (the probability of it NOT occurring)','EMV cannot be calculated without knowing the project\'s risk appetite'], correct:1, explanation:'EMV = P × I = 40% × $200,000 = $80,000 represents the statistical expected cost of this risk. This informs contingency reserve: if we managed 10 similar projects, the average cost of this risk would be $80,000. For contingency reserve, using EMV sum across risks is appropriate. HOWEVER: the actual response plan must prepare for the full $200,000/$4-week scenario — because if the risk fires, it doesn\'t fire at 40% magnitude, it fires at 100%. EMV determines the reserve; the full scenario determines the response plan. Both calculations are necessary. The schedule EMV (1.6 weeks) similarly informs schedule contingency, while the full 4-week response must be pre-planned.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is reviewing a network diagram. Activity F has an Early Start (ES) of Day 10, Early Finish (EF) of Day 18, Late Start (LS) of Day 15, Late Finish (LF) of Day 23.', question:'What is the Total Float for Activity F and what does it mean?', options:['Float = 0 (Activity F is on the critical path)','Total Float = LS − ES = 15 − 10 = 5 days (also: LF − EF = 23 − 18 = 5). This means Activity F can be delayed up to 5 days without impacting the project end date. Activity F is NOT on the critical path since it has positive float.','Float = 5 days and Activity F is on the critical path','Float = 8 days based on EF − ES = 18 − 10'], correct:1, explanation:'Total Float = LS − ES = 15 − 10 = 5 days (equivalently, LF − EF = 23 − 18 = 5 days — both calculations give the same result). Activity F can be delayed up to 5 days without delaying the project end date. An activity is on the critical path if and only if Total Float = 0. With 5 days of float, F is NOT critical. Note: Early Start/Finish calculated via forward pass (add durations); Late Start/Finish via backward pass (subtract durations). Float = the scheduling flexibility available. These calculations are a guaranteed PMP exam math question type.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is using Earned Value Management to track a 12-month project. At the 6-month mark: BAC = $600K, PV = $350K, EV = $300K, AC = $320K.', question:'What is the Estimate to Complete (ETC) using the most common formula?', options:['ETC = $280K (BAC − EV, assuming remaining work is re-estimated)','CPI = EV/AC = 300/320 = 0.9375. ETC = (BAC − EV)/CPI = ($600K − $300K)/0.9375 = $300K/0.9375 = $320K. This assumes current cost efficiency (CPI = 0.9375) will continue for remaining work. EAC = AC + ETC = $320K + $320K = $640K (forecast overrun of $40K).','ETC = $300K (remaining BAC)','ETC = $280K (BAC − AC = $600K − $320K)'], correct:1, explanation:'ETC (Estimate to Complete) = cost needed to complete remaining work. Most common formula (assuming current CPI continues): ETC = (BAC − EV) / CPI = ($600K − $300K) / 0.9375 = $300K / 0.9375 = $320,000. The alternative formula — ETC = BAC − EV = $300K — assumes the remaining work will be done at original budgeted efficiency (when original estimate was atypical). Using the CPI-adjusted formula acknowledges that current over-spending efficiency (CPI = 0.9375) will likely continue. EAC = AC + ETC = $320K + $320K = $640K, forecasting a $40K overrun. Know which formula to use in which scenario — the exam tests this distinction.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is planning a high-risk research and development project. The project involves multiple technical unknowns. The sponsor wants a detailed 18-month plan with locked milestones.', question:'What should the project manager recommend as the planning approach?', options:['Create the detailed 18-month plan as requested — sponsors require certainty','Recommend an iterative/phase-gate approach with 3-month detailed planning windows and 18-month strategic milestones. Explain to the sponsor that in R&D projects, technical unknowns make detailed long-range planning unreliable — phase gates allow go/no-go decisions based on actual discovery, protecting the organization from continued investment if the technical path proves unviable.','Create the plan but add 50% contingency to all estimates','Refuse to plan beyond 3 months since R&D cannot be predicted'], correct:1, explanation:'R&D projects have characteristics that make detailed long-range planning unreliable: technical unknowns, discovery-driven work, hypotheses that may prove false. The professional response: distinguish between strategic milestones (decision points for continued investment — appropriate to lock) and detailed activity plans (unreliable at 12-18 month horizon — use rolling wave). Phase-gate approach: detailed planning for the current phase, strategic objectives for future phases, go/no-go decisions at each gate based on discoveries. This protects the organization from plan-driven R&D investment in directions that technical discovery shows are unviable. This is appropriate tailoring of planning to project type (PMBOK 7 Principle #7).' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'During project execution, the project manager receives a contractor\'s invoice for $85,000. The project\'s records show only $72,000 of contracted deliverables have been accepted and documented.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Pay the invoice to maintain the contractor relationship','Do not approve payment for uninspected deliverables. Identify the $13,000 discrepancy, verify what deliverables were actually accepted vs. what the invoice claims, resolve the discrepancy with the vendor (is this advance billing? disputed work? billing error?), and only approve payment for verified, formally accepted deliverables. Document all dispute communications.','Pay the invoice and reconcile later','Reject the entire invoice since there is any discrepancy'], correct:1, explanation:'Invoice management requires matching payment to formally accepted deliverables. Paying $85K for $72K of verified work creates financial and audit risk. The PM must: identify the specific $13K discrepancy (which line items?), verify against acceptance records, communicate the discrepancy to the vendor with specific documentation, and approve only the $72K verified portion while resolving the $13K question. Common causes: advance billing for work in progress (may be allowed by contract terms), billing for work that wasn\'t formally accepted but was delivered, or billing error. Resolution depends on contract terms. This is contract administration and financial control.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is evaluating schedule performance for a project using both traditional EVM metrics and agile velocity tracking. The EVM shows SPI = 0.90, but the agile velocity chart shows the team is consistently hitting their sprint commitments.', question:'How should the PM reconcile these apparently contradictory signals?', options:['Trust the agile velocity data since the team is meeting sprint commitments','Investigate the discrepancy: EVM SPI measures progress against the planned value curve; agile velocity measures throughput against sprint commitments. If the sprint commitments were revised down (capacity planning was adjusted for team availability), hitting the commitment doesn\'t mean the overall project is on schedule. The discrepancy likely means planned project milestones are at risk even though the team is executing their sprints well.','Trust EVM since it is the more traditional and rigorous metric','Both metrics are measuring the same thing — the discrepancy is a measurement error'], correct:1, explanation:'This is a sophisticated hybrid project management scenario. SPI = 0.90 means the project is behind its original planned value schedule. Consistent sprint velocity hitting might be because: (1) Sprint commitments were reduced (adjusted downward from the original plan), (2) The original project schedule was over-optimistic, or (3) There are planned features in the project baseline that haven\'t been included in sprint planning yet. The discrepancy is diagnostic information: investigate what\'s IN the EVM plan but not yet in sprint backlogs, and whether the team\'s capacity adjustments have created a project schedule gap. Both metrics provide useful but different views.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is preparing the closing documentation for a major project. The project delivered all contractually specified deliverables but the client is dissatisfied with the outcome, feeling the product doesn\'t meet their original intent.', question:'What does this situation indicate about the project\'s quality of requirements?', options:['The project was successful since all contractual requirements were met','This indicates a requirements quality failure: the contract specifications did not accurately capture the client\'s true needs (intent vs. specification gap). Deliverables can be contractually compliant but still fail to meet user intent — especially when requirements were written without sufficient stakeholder involvement, prototyping, or validation. Lessons learned: requirements need validated against user intent, not just written down.','The client is wrong since contractual requirements were met','The PM is responsible for delivering to specifications — client satisfaction is the sponsor\'s concern'], correct:1, explanation:'This scenario illustrates the classic requirements-reality gap: meeting specifications ≠ meeting needs. The root cause is requirements quality failure — the specifications didn\'t capture what the client actually needed. This is the "validated requirements" principle: requirements should be validated against user needs through prototypes, walkthroughs, and acceptance testing BEFORE they become the contractual basis. The lesson for future projects: involve end users in requirements validation (not just sponsors), prototype to validate understanding, include stakeholder acceptance as a process gate. Contractual compliance is the floor of project success, not the ceiling. True success is client satisfaction with the outcome.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is closing a contract with a vendor. The vendor has met all contractual requirements, but the project team discovered that the vendor\'s solution has significant technical debt that will increase future maintenance costs.', question:'What should the PM do?', options:['Pay the final invoice and close the contract since contractual requirements were met','Pay the final invoice and close the contract since requirements were met. Document the technical debt as a formal project lessons learned item. Ensure the technical debt risk is transferred to the operations team with full documentation of the debt\'s nature and estimated future cost. Consider whether future contracts with this vendor should include non-functional requirements (code quality standards, maintainability metrics) explicitly.','Withhold final payment until the technical debt is resolved','Request a contract extension to address technical debt before closing'], correct:1, explanation:'If technical debt was not specified as a contractual requirement, the vendor has technically fulfilled their obligations — withholding payment creates legal liability. However: the technical debt is a real organizational risk that must be managed. The PM\'s closure responsibilities: pay the final invoice (contract closure), formally document the technical debt (what it is, estimated future cost, affected systems) in lessons learned, transfer this risk knowledge to the operations team with recommendations, and update procurement templates to include code quality and maintainability standards for future contracts. This is responsible project closure — managing the full lifecycle impact of project decisions.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager needs to select among four projects to recommend to the portfolio committee, given limited budget. The projects have the following NPVs and strategic scores: Project A: NPV $2M, Strategic Score 3/5. Project B: NPV $800K, Strategic Score 5/5. Project C: NPV $1.5M, Strategic Score 4/5. Project D: NPV $3M, Strategic Score 1/5.', question:'What recommendation framework should be used?', options:['Always recommend the highest NPV project (Project D) regardless of strategic score','Use a weighted scoring model: assign weights to NPV and Strategic Score based on organizational priorities. If the organization is maximizing financial return (70% weight NPV, 30% weight strategic): Project D likely wins. If strategically driven (30% NPV, 70% strategic): Project B or C likely wins. The recommendation must reflect and explicitly state the weighting rationale.','Always recommend the highest strategic score (Project B) regardless of NPV','Average NPV and strategic score equally for all projects'], correct:1, explanation:'Portfolio selection is a multi-criteria decision that should be transparent and traceable. The right approach: establish weights based on the organization\'s stated strategic priorities BEFORE evaluating projects (to prevent retroactive rationalization). Apply the weights: Weighted Score = (NPV weight × normalized NPV score) + (Strategic weight × strategic score). The recommendation should state: "Based on our weighting of 60% financial return and 40% strategic alignment, Project C scores highest and is recommended." This process is auditable, consistent, and aligned with the organization\'s values. Pure NPV selection (option A) ignores strategy; pure strategy selection (option C) ignores financial viability.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'An agile team has consistently achieved 80% of their sprint commitments over 8 sprints. The Scrum Master suggests this shows healthy planning with appropriate stretch. The PM disagrees.', question:'Who is correct and why?', options:['The Scrum Master is correct — 80% is a healthy achievement rate that prevents over-commitment','Both are partially right, but 80% consistently means the team is either chronically over-committing or has a systematic execution impediment. Healthy agile teams should achieve 85-95% of sprint commitments consistently. At 80%, there is likely a predictable and addressable root cause: unclear acceptance criteria? Hidden external dependencies? Consistent mid-sprint scope additions? Investigation and improvement are warranted.','The PM is correct — 80% means 20% of sprint work is consistently wasted','Consistent 80% achievement is ideal for maximizing stretch and team learning'], correct:1, explanation:'There is no universally "right" sprint commitment achievement rate — the goal is empirical reliability. However, consistently achieving 80% over 8 sprints indicates a pattern that should be investigated. Random variation (some sprints 70%, some 95%) might be acceptable. Consistent 80% suggests a systematic issue: stories are consistently estimated 20% too optimistically, or there is a recurring mid-sprint disruption (scope additions, dependency failures, unavailability). The investigation question: what specifically prevents the remaining 20% from completing? Once identified, the team can address the root cause. "Stretch" planning (intentionally setting commitments you can\'t achieve) violates the empirical commitment principle of Scrum.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is creating the risk register for a new infrastructure project. A team member says: "We don\'t need to register risks we have already mitigated — only open risks belong in the register."', question:'Is this correct?', options:['Yes — only unmitigated, open risks should be in the risk register','No — the risk register should document all identified risks including: active risks with their response strategies and status, risks that have been closed with their actual impact, risks that have been mitigated (to show residual risk level), and risks that have been escalated. A complete register provides audit trail, informs future projects, and shows the total risk management picture.','Yes — closed risks should be moved to a lessons learned document only','Yes — the register should only contain risks above the probability/impact threshold'], correct:1, explanation:'A complete risk register is a comprehensive record, not just a list of current open threats. It should document: (1) All identified risks with their probability/impact assessment. (2) Risks with planned responses (mitigation, contingency) and their status. (3) Risks that materialized as issues and their actual impact. (4) Closed risks (expired, or resolved) — these form the historical record for future projects. (5) Escalated risks and their resolution. The risk register is a living project management document AND an OPA input for future projects. Removing closed/mitigated risks destroys organizational learning. A register showing only "scary open risks" also doesn\'t show the PM\'s proactive risk management work.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is conducting sprint retrospectives, but the action items identified never get implemented because the team "doesn\'t have time" during sprints to work on process improvements.', question:'What systemic problem does this identify and what is the solution?', options:['Retrospectives should be less frequent if their output isn\'t implemented','The team has not committed capacity for improvement work. Solution: treat retrospective action items as first-class sprint backlog items — they have an "owner" who is accountable, are estimated and prioritized just like feature work, and are tracked in the sprint review. The concept of "improvement capacity" (5-10% of sprint capacity reserved for process improvement) formally acknowledges that improvement is work, not optional overhead.','Stop conducting retrospectives since they are not producing value','Make retrospective action items the responsibility of the Scrum Master only'], correct:1, explanation:'Kaizen (continuous improvement) is a core agile principle. Retrospectives have zero value if action items are never implemented. The structural fix: formalize improvement work as sprint backlog items. This means: the team estimates the effort required, an owner is assigned and accountable, and the item appears in the sprint review with its completion status visible to stakeholders. An "improvement capacity" allocation (e.g., 1 story point per sprint dedicated to process improvement) creates the systematic time for it. Making it SM-only (option D) removes team ownership. Less frequent retros (option A) reduces feedback cycles. This is kaizen operationalized — continuous improvement as a structural practice.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project is in execution when a new regulatory requirement is announced that will require significant rework of an already-completed deliverable. The rework is estimated at $150K and 6 weeks.', question:'What type of change is this and how should it be handled?', options:['This is a corrective action — the PM should implement it immediately without change request since it\'s regulatory','This is a regulatory-driven scope change requiring formal change control: document the regulatory requirement (source, effective date, specific requirements), conduct an impact analysis ($150K cost, 6-week schedule impact, quality implications of rework), submit a change request to the CCB (regulatory changes are legitimate and typically approved, but the impact must be formally documented and the baseline updated), and communicate to stakeholders.','This is a defect repair since the deliverable doesn\'t meet regulatory requirements','This is an emergency — implement first and document later'], correct:1, explanation:'Regulatory changes are legitimate scope changes, not defects. The deliverable met its specifications at the time it was built — the regulations changed after. This distinction matters for: cost responsibility (who pays?), schedule baseline update, and stakeholder communication. Even though regulatory compliance is non-negotiable, the process is still: document → analyze impact → CCB review → approve → update baselines → implement. For truly time-critical regulatory deadlines, the CCB review can be expedited but not skipped. The type classification matters: scope change (new regulatory requirement) affects baselines and has cost/schedule implications that must be formally managed.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is planning a global software rollout. The rollout will be implemented in 5 regional waves to manage risk. If the first wave reveals problems, subsequent waves can be adjusted.', question:'What project management approach does this represent?', options:['Critical Chain Method — protecting the project with buffers','Phased/staged rollout with iterative refinement — this is a risk management technique where early waves serve as controlled pilots that provide feedback to improve subsequent waves. It combines elements of predictive (planned wave schedule) and adaptive (incorporate learnings between waves) approaches.','Pure waterfall — sequential implementation is always waterfall','Monte Carlo simulation applied to deployment planning'], correct:1, explanation:'A phased global rollout is a risk management strategy that uses early deployment phases as real-world pilots. This is not purely waterfall (which would deploy all 5 regions simultaneously after a single plan) or purely agile (which would use shorter cycles). It is an intelligent hybrid: the overall rollout plan is predictive (5 waves, defined regions, scheduled dates), but the adaptive element is the feedback loop between waves (what did wave 1 teach us? how do we adjust waves 2-5?). This reduces systemic rollout risk by limiting initial exposure. It\'s increasingly tested on PMP exams as hybrid project management approaches become more common.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is facilitating a project risk workshop. A team member proposes the risk: "The project will fail." Other team members laugh. The risk workshop facilitator asks the team to formalize it.', question:'What is wrong with "The project will fail" as a risk statement?', options:['Nothing — it is a legitimate risk that must be managed','It is too vague to be actionable. A proper risk statement follows the format: "Due to [cause], [risk event] may occur, which could result in [impact]." "Project failure" is an outcome category, not a specific risk. The team should identify SPECIFIC risks: "Due to technical integration complexity, the API integration may fail testing, which could delay delivery by 4 weeks." Specific risks enable specific responses.','It is too pessimistic and should be reframed positively','It is an assumption, not a risk, and belongs in the assumption log'], correct:1, explanation:'Risk quality is about actionability. "The project will fail" is: too vague to plan a response for, not a specific triggering event, and a tautology (all projects have this "risk"). The three-part risk statement — Cause/Risk/Impact — produces actionable risk entries. Cause: the condition that creates the risk. Risk: the uncertain event that might occur. Impact: the consequence if it does. Example: "Due to dependency on third-party API [cause], the API may be deprecated during project [risk], which could require 6 weeks of redesign [impact]." This specific statement enables specific monitoring (API vendor announcements), specific responses (API abstraction layer), and specific triggers (deprecation announcement).' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is managing a government defense project with strict security classification requirements. The project uses a predictive approach with detailed phase-gate reviews. During execution, the PM realizes that the project\'s technical approach needs to change significantly due to a technical discovery.', question:'What is the correct process for implementing this change?', options:['Implement the change immediately since technical discoveries are legitimate','Document the technical discovery and its implications, conduct a detailed impact analysis on scope, schedule, cost, security classification, and risk, submit a formal Engineering Change Proposal (ECP) through the appropriate change control board (with security classification appropriate routing), update all affected controlled documents, and implement only after all required approvals are obtained.','Notify the project sponsor verbally and proceed with the change','Wait for the next scheduled phase gate to propose the change'], correct:1, explanation:'Defense projects operate under Configuration Management (CM) regimes that are even more stringent than standard PMI change control. An Engineering Change Proposal (ECP) is the formal instrument for technical baseline changes in defense contracts. The routing must respect security classification (only cleared personnel can review classified technical changes). Verbal sponsor notification without formal ECP creates audit and compliance risk. Waiting for the phase gate delays necessary response. The correct behavior is always: document → analyze → formal change proposal through appropriate classified channels → approved change implementation. This is compliance-driven change management in a regulated environment.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is conducting the Monitor and Control Project Work process. The team has prepared work performance information showing schedule and cost variances. The PM must now decide what to do.', question:'What are the outputs the PM should produce from this monitoring cycle?', options:['A corrective action implemented immediately','Work Performance Reports (formatted for stakeholder distribution), Change Requests (if variances require scope/schedule/cost changes to baselines), and updates to relevant project documents and PM Plan. Additionally: forecast updates (EAC, ETC), risk register updates if variance reveals new risks, and communication to relevant stakeholders.','Only verbal communication to the team about variances','Issue log updates only'], correct:1, explanation:'Monitor and Control Project Work (Process 4.5) has specific outputs defined in PMBOK 6: Work Performance Reports (packaging information for stakeholder communication — dashboards, status reports), Change Requests (when variances indicate need for baseline changes), and updates to the Project Management Plan and Project Documents. Beyond PMBOK outputs: EAC/ETC forecast updates (quantify forward-looking impact), risk register updates (do variances reveal new or escalated risks?), and appropriate stakeholder communication. Immediate corrective action without formal documentation skips the change control step. This is the full monitoring-to-action cycle that the PMP exam tests.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project manager is working on a residential construction project. The project plan shows that painting can begin as soon as each room\'s walls are plastered, without waiting for all rooms to be complete.', question:'What type of dependency does this represent?', options:['Mandatory Dependency — painting must always wait for all plaster to cure','Discretionary Dependency — this is a preferred sequencing but could logically be changed','Finish-to-Start with Lead — painting in Room A can begin a fixed number of days after Room A plastering finishes (lead = allowed overlap between predecessor finish and successor start). This is not a full Finish-to-Start dependency.','Start-to-Start Dependency — painting and plastering start simultaneously'], correct:2, explanation:'This is a Lead relationship applied to a Finish-to-Start dependency. Each room\'s painting has a Finish-to-Start relationship with that room\'s plastering (painting starts after plastering finishes) — but with a specific technical requirement: plaster must cure for 24-48 hours before painting (a specific lag). Painting can begin in Room 1 while Room 2 is still being plastered — this is parallel work enabled by room-level sequencing, not project-level sequencing. The "each room independently" structure creates multiple parallel Finish-to-Start (with lag for curing) relationships by room. Understanding leads, lags, and dependency types is a PMP exam schedule management requirement.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project team is using Kanban for operational support work. The team\'s average lead time (from request to delivery) has increased from 3 days to 9 days over the past 2 months.', question:'What does this indicate and how should it be analyzed?', options:['Lead time fluctuation is normal in support work — no action needed','A tripling of lead time over 2 months is a significant degradation signal. Use cumulative flow diagram (CFD) to identify WHERE work is accumulating (which Kanban column has growing queues?), analyze whether WIP limits are being respected, identify whether specific work types are taking longer, and investigate whether team capacity has decreased or demand has increased.','Extend WIP limits to accommodate more work','Set a SLA target and measure how many items miss it'], correct:1, explanation:'Lead time is the primary customer-facing quality metric in Kanban — it directly measures the service delivery experience. A 3× increase indicates a systemic problem. Root cause analysis using Kanban metrics: Cumulative Flow Diagram (CFD) shows which stage is accumulating work (where is the bottleneck?). WIP monitoring shows whether limits are being violated. Type-of-work analysis shows if specific request categories are consistently slow. Demand vs. capacity analysis shows whether request volume has outpaced team capacity. Each diagnosis leads to a different corrective action. Setting SLA targets without diagnosis (option D) measures the problem more precisely without addressing it. Extending WIP limits (option C) typically worsens lead time by allowing more concurrent work.' },
  { domain:'Process', scenario:'A project is being managed with a hybrid approach. The predictive portions are baselined and tracked with EVM. The agile portions use velocity. The project sponsor wants a single integrated performance report.', question:'What should the PM include in this integrated report?', options:['Separate sections for predictive and agile metrics with no integration','An integrated executive summary showing: total project progress (predictive baselines vs. actuals for baselined scope + agile completed story points vs. planned for agile scope), key milestones status, combined risk summary, and a unified forecast — translating agile velocity-based forecasts into milestone dates and cost equivalents to complement EVM data from predictive phases.','Convert all agile data to EVM format for consistency','Report only EVM data since it is more rigorous'], correct:1, explanation:'Hybrid project management requires hybrid reporting. Sponsors need an integrated picture: overall project health, not separate methodology-siloed views. An effective integrated report: (1) Progress: predictive phases tracked against EVM baselines; agile phases tracked against velocity/backlog; a combined completion percentage. (2) Milestone status: all major milestones (regardless of methodology) tracked against expected dates. (3) Risk: combined risk register summary. (4) Forecast: agile velocity converted to release date estimates; EVM EAC for predictive cost. The key skill: translating between metric systems (story points to schedule, velocity to completion date) to provide a coherent narrative. This is a PM integrating function at its most sophisticated.' },

// ─────────────────────────── BUSINESS ENVIRONMENT (~14 questions) ───────────────────────────
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is managing a product development project. Three months before the planned product launch, market research reveals that the target customer segment has significantly different preferences than the product\'s current design assumes.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Continue with the current design since the project plan cannot be changed at this stage','Escalate the market research findings to the sponsor and steering committee immediately with: an analysis of the gap between current design and discovered preferences, the cost and timeline of design modifications, and the risk of launching a misaligned product vs. delaying for modification. Present options with trade-offs, not just the problem.','Adjust the product design independently to reflect the new market findings','Document the discrepancy and address it in a product update after launch'], correct:1, explanation:'Market misalignment discovered pre-launch is a critical business environment change that requires immediate executive attention. The PM cannot make the strategic decision (modify design vs. launch as-is), but must ensure decision-makers have: the specific nature of the misalignment (which design elements conflict with discovered preferences), cost and schedule impact of modification vs. current plan, business risk of launching misaligned (market failure probability, brand impact), and the PM\'s recommended path. This is PMBOK 7 Principle #4 (Focus on Value) — proactively surfacing threats to the project\'s ability to deliver its intended business value.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is working on a project to digitize a government archive. Midway through, a change in government administration results in new leadership that wants to re-prioritize the digitization scope to focus on different document types than originally planned.', question:'What should the project manager do?', options:['Refuse to change scope since the project charter was signed by the previous administration','Work with the new leadership to: understand their specific scope priorities, assess the impact of re-prioritization on completed work, current contracts, and remaining timeline, prepare a formal change request for CCB review, and adapt the project scope to reflect the new administration\'s priorities through proper governance channels.','Complete the project with the original scope and let new leadership decide what to do with results','Terminate the project since the original strategic intent has changed'], correct:1, explanation:'Government projects are particularly susceptible to political/administration changes. New leadership bringing different priorities is a legitimate EEF change that must be managed professionally. The PM\'s role: serve the organization (now represented by new leadership), facilitate the scope re-prioritization through proper governance (CCB), protect stakeholders who may be affected by the change (contractors with current scopes, communities waiting for specific document types), and update baselines accordingly. Refusing to adapt to legitimate new authority is organizational non-compliance. Complete termination is extreme without investigating whether the project can be re-scoped to serve new priorities. Change management through governance is the correct path.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'An organization is launching multiple projects simultaneously under a strategic initiative. The PMO identifies that collectively the projects require 140% of available IT capacity. Several projects will be delayed.', question:'What resource optimization approach is MOST appropriate?', options:['Start all projects simultaneously and let resource conflicts resolve themselves','At the portfolio level: conduct priority ranking of all projects in the initiative, calculate resource requirements per quarter for each project, use resource leveling across projects (adjust start dates to smooth demand below capacity while preserving highest-priority projects\' timelines), and communicate delay decisions transparently to affected project stakeholders with the strategic rationale.','Hire 40% additional IT capacity immediately','Request that all project managers reduce their resource estimates'], correct:1, explanation:'Portfolio-level resource leveling is the standard response to aggregate resource overallocation. The process: (1) Prioritize projects by strategic value and interdependency. (2) Map resource demand by period across all projects. (3) Adjust start dates of lower-priority projects to reduce peak demand below capacity. (4) Communicate delay rationale transparently (prioritization framework, not arbitrary selection). (5) Monitor resource demand as projects progress and re-adjust. "Resolve themselves" (option A) means the most aggressive teams get resources regardless of strategic priority. Hiring 40% immediately (option C) may be appropriate for critical projects but can\'t be the universal answer. Requesting estimate reduction (option D) creates unreliable plans.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is launching a mobile application that will collect user location data for a personalized experience. The legal team advises that different countries have different location data regulations (GDPR in EU, different standards elsewhere).', question:'What must the project manager ensure is included in the project scope?', options:['One universal privacy approach that satisfies the most restrictive regulation everywhere','Jurisdiction-specific privacy compliance as explicit project scope: geo-specific consent mechanisms (GDPR-compliant for EU users, CCPA-compliant for California users), data localization where required, jurisdiction-specific data retention policies, a compliance verification process with legal review for each target market, and ongoing regulatory monitoring for changes post-launch.','Launch in the least regulated markets first, then address regulatory markets later','Ask the legal team to handle compliance separately from the project'], correct:1, explanation:'Multi-jurisdiction privacy compliance for location data is a project scope requirement, not a legal add-on. Each jurisdiction has specific requirements: GDPR requires explicit granular consent, right to be forgotten, data portability, and breach notification within 72 hours. CCPA requires disclosure and opt-out mechanisms. Other jurisdictions have their own requirements. The PM must: include jurisdiction-specific compliance as explicit WBS deliverables, budget for legal review in each market, design technical architecture to support geo-specific data handling (data localization, user consent storage, deletion workflows), and establish ongoing regulatory monitoring. A single "most restrictive" approach (option A) may over-comply in some markets and under-comply in others.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is conducting a benefits realization review 12 months after project completion. The project was supposed to deliver 20% cost reduction through process automation. Actual cost reduction is 8%.', question:'What analysis should the benefits owner conduct?', options:['Accept the 8% as the final outcome and close the benefits tracking','Conduct a benefits gap analysis: what specifically prevented the full 20% realization? Common causes: adoption gap (automation tools implemented but users still using manual processes), scope gap (some automation was implemented but not all planned features), baseline error (original 20% estimate was too optimistic), or external changes (process costs declined generally, reducing the automation benefit). Each cause has different implications for corrective action.','Blame the project team for underdelivering','Report the shortfall and close benefits tracking since the project is complete'], correct:1, explanation:'A 12% gap between promised and actual benefits is significant and warrants root cause analysis. Benefits shortfalls have identifiable causes: adoption gap (users not using the automation = training/change management failure), implementation gap (not all automation features were delivered = project scope gap), measurement gap (benefits were measured incorrectly), or assumption failure (the 20% estimate assumed conditions that didn\'t materialize). Each cause has a different corrective action: adoption gap → reinforced training and management enforcement; implementation gap → additional development; assumption failure → lessons learned for future benefit estimation. Without diagnosis, the organizational learning is lost.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'An organization implements a zero-based budgeting approach for project portfolios. This means that each project must re-justify its budget every year, regardless of multi-year commitments.', question:'How should project managers respond to this organizational change?', options:['Resist zero-based budgeting since it threatens multi-year project commitments','Understand the organizational rationale (financial discipline, value accountability), adapt project documentation to support annual re-justification (benefits realized to date, remaining expected value, updated completion cost forecast), and advocate for transition mechanisms that protect projects with strong business cases from unnecessary re-work of already-completed planning.','Accept annual budget disruption as inevitable and plan around it','Frontload as much spending as possible in the first year to avoid re-justification risk'], correct:1, explanation:'Zero-based budgeting is a legitimate organizational governance mechanism that requires PM adaptation, not resistance. Practical adaptation: annual project "mini-business case" updates showing benefits realized, remaining value, updated completion forecast, and strategic alignment. The PM should also advocate for portfolio-level transition provisions: projects with 80%+ completion or with contractual commitments should have expedited re-justification paths. Front-loading spending (option D) creates poor financial governance and cash flow problems. Resistance (option A) fails the organizational compliance obligation. The PM\'s role is to make the project\'s value visible through the new budgeting lens — which is actually good project management practice.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager has been notified that the organization is planning to use carbon offset reporting for all capital projects going forward. The PM must now include environmental impact assessment in future project planning.', question:'What should the project manager do to incorporate this requirement?', options:['Delegate environmental assessment entirely to a sustainability team','Integrate environmental impact as a formal project constraint and deliverable: include carbon footprint assessment in the project scope (possibly as a WBS element), engage sustainability expertise for the assessment, include environmental metrics in the success criteria, and ensure environmental impacts are considered in key project decisions (vendor selection, materials choice, transportation methods).','Conduct a rough environmental assessment and document it informally','Address environmental requirements only at the organizational level, not project level'], correct:1, explanation:'Environmental governance requirements are EEFs (organizational policies) that become project constraints when mandated by the organization. Integration means: including carbon footprint calculation as a legitimate project deliverable (with budget and schedule), considering environmental impact in major decisions (e.g., local vs. international vendors for transportation emissions, sustainable materials selection), and including environmental performance metrics in project success measurement alongside traditional cost/schedule/scope. This reflects PMBOK 7 Principle #1 (Stewardship — including environmental stewardship) and the increasing importance of ESG (Environmental, Social, Governance) considerations in project management. The PM cannot outsource this to sustainability teams while ignoring it in project decisions.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A company\'s enterprise risk committee identifies that a portfolio of technology projects collectively creates a cybersecurity vulnerability: each project has its own security architecture, creating integration security gaps.', question:'What should the portfolio manager/PM recommend?', options:['Each project should address its own security requirements independently','Recommend an enterprise security architecture review that spans all projects: identify the integration security gaps, establish common security standards that all projects must implement, create a shared security architecture that individual projects build within (not around), and implement enterprise-level security testing that covers cross-project integration points — treating the portfolio collectively as the security attack surface.','Terminate the project with the weakest security architecture','Add security resources to each individual project team'], correct:1, explanation:'Cybersecurity at the portfolio level requires systems thinking (PMBOK 7 Principle #5) — the collective attack surface of integrated systems is different from the sum of individual project attack surfaces. Integration gaps (how System A passes data to System B, authentication between systems, shared credential stores) are visible only at the portfolio level. The recommendation: enterprise security architecture that defines mandatory standards and integration patterns for all projects, combined with enterprise-level penetration testing that exercises cross-project integration points. Individual project-level security is necessary but insufficient. This is portfolio-level risk management applied to cybersecurity.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager\'s organization decides to implement a blockchain-based supply chain system. The PM notes that the technology is immature in the industry and no proven implementation patterns exist for this specific use case.', question:'What project approach and risk strategy is MOST appropriate?', options:['Use a fully predictive approach since blockchain technology is well-established globally','Use an iterative/experimental approach: start with a proof-of-concept sprint, establish technical feasibility before full commitment, maintain a decision point (go/no-go) at PoC completion, and explicitly acknowledge in the project charter that the technology maturity risk may result in project termination or significant scope modification. Manage stakeholder expectations on this uncertainty proactively.','Proceed with full implementation based on available technical documentation','Terminate the project since immature technology projects have too high a risk'], correct:1, explanation:'Emerging technology projects with no proven implementation patterns require an empirical, discovery-driven approach. A Proof of Concept (PoC) phase: defines a specific technical hypothesis to test (can blockchain provide X benefit for our Y use case?), is timeboxed (2-4 sprints), produces a go/no-go decision point, and limits investment exposure before technical feasibility is proven. This is NOT the same as terminating the project — it\'s responsible phased commitment. The project charter must explicitly acknowledge the technology maturity risk. Stakeholder expectations should be calibrated: "we will learn by the end of sprint 4 whether this technology meets our needs." This is innovation-risk governance.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is planning a conference event. The event\'s success depends heavily on external factors: speaker availability, attendee registration numbers, and venue conditions. All three have high uncertainty.', question:'What risk management approach is MOST effective for event projects?', options:['Accept all uncertainty since events are inherently unpredictable','Use scenario planning: develop best-case, most-likely, and worst-case scenarios for the key uncertainty drivers. For each scenario, define trigger-based response plans: "If registration falls below X by date Y, we will Z." Create decision trees for vendor dependency failures. Build in flexibility contracts (venue contracts with cancellation/modification provisions, speaker contract with substitution clauses).','Create a detailed fixed plan and enforce it regardless of changing conditions','Focus risk management only on the highest-probability risk'], correct:1, explanation:'Event projects have high external dependency and environmental uncertainty that makes single-point planning unreliable. Scenario planning acknowledges this: best-case (all speakers confirmed, registration exceeds target, weather perfect), most-likely, and worst-case scenarios. Trigger-based response plans create pre-authorized action paths that enable fast response without real-time approval processes ("if speaker drops out less than 48 hours before event, activate speaker B who has been pre-briefed"). Flexible contracts preserve response options. This is risk response planning tailored to event management characteristics — proactive scenario design rather than reactive crisis management.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A project manager is closing a project that was originally intended to develop an AI customer service chatbot. During the project, the team discovered that the AI approach was not technically viable and pivoted to a rule-based system. The pivot delivered functional value but was not what was originally chartered.', question:'What closing documentation issue must the PM address?', options:['Close the project against the original charter objectives since that was the authorized plan','Document the pivot explicitly in closure documentation: original charter objectives, the point at which the pivot decision was made and by whom (authorized change), what was actually delivered vs. originally chartered, the rationale for the pivot (technical discovery), the business value of what was delivered, and any residual gap between original intent and actual delivery. Archive the technical findings on AI limitations as organizational learning.','Close the project as if the original objectives were met to simplify reporting','Recommend project termination since the original objectives were not met'], correct:1, explanation:'Honest project closure documentation requires accurately representing what happened, not what was originally planned. The closure report is an organizational record that: documents the original charter, the authorized change decision (who authorized the pivot, when, why), the actual deliverables and their relationship to original objectives, business value delivered, and technical learnings (AI limitations for this use case — valuable OPA for future AI projects). Documenting against the original charter as if the pivot didn\'t happen is historical falsification. Terminating because the original objectives weren\'t met ignores the value of the adapted delivery. This is honest project closure — a governance and organizational learning obligation.' },
  { domain:'Business Environment', scenario:'A PMO is considering implementing a benefit-tracking dashboard that will show real-time benefit realization data for all completed projects. Several project sponsors resist, saying "we\'ve already closed these projects."', question:'What is the PMO\'s strongest argument for continuing benefits tracking post-closure?', options:['Benefits tracking is bureaucratic overhead that adds cost without value','Benefits realization data is the organization\'s primary evidence of whether project investments deliver their promised returns. Without tracking, the organization cannot: validate investment decisions retrospectively, improve future business case quality, identify adoption or change management gaps that are eroding benefits, or demonstrate portfolio ROI to governance bodies. The data enables smarter future investment decisions.','Benefits tracking is the project team\'s ongoing responsibility post-closure','Benefits are automatically realized when deliverables are deployed — tracking is unnecessary'], correct:1, explanation:'Post-project benefits tracking serves critical organizational learning and governance functions. Evidence of benefit realization: (1) enables the organization to validate that business cases are realistic (or identifies systematic overestimation that inflates portfolio value), (2) reveals adoption or change management gaps that are eroding benefits (enabling corrective action while recovery is still possible), (3) demonstrates portfolio ROI to executive governance, (4) improves future business case quality through calibration. "We\'ve already closed" conflates project closure with benefits realization — projects close, but their value (or lack thereof) continues to accumulate in operations. Benefits tracking is the organizational accountability mechanism for capital investment decisions.' },
];
